body:
Given the following code ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=18b70dc967a80be7c93640e7fc09bb16)):

```rust
use std::io::Read;

struct Foo {
    inner: Option<Box<dyn Read>>,
}

impl Foo {
    fn member(&mut self) {
        bar(self.inner.as_deref_mut());
    }
}

fn bar(read: Option<&mut dyn Read>) {
    
}


fn main() {
  let mut foo = Foo { inner: None };
  foo.member();
}
```

The current output (on stable and nightly) is:

```
   Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
error[E0759]: `self` has an anonymous lifetime `'_` but it needs to satisfy a `'static` lifetime requirement
 --> src/main.rs:9:24
  |
8 |     fn member(&mut self) {
  |               --------- this data with an anonymous lifetime `'_`...
9 |         bar(self.inner.as_deref_mut());
  |             ---------- ^^^^^^^^^^^^
  |             |
  |             ...is used and required to live as long as `'static` here

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0759`.
error: could not compile `playground` due to previous error
```

I can't work out where the 'static lifetime requirement is coming from here.

Is it possible the compiler is confused by the multiple de-references here?
